summary:
I am currently working towards a law degree at McGill University. I am passionate about bridging science and law, particularly in relation to big data and artificial intelligence policy, data analytics, brain-machine interactions, and empirical legal research. I recently obtained a Ph.D. in Neuroscience from the University of Alberta. My research focused on how electrical brain stimulation can be used to influence brain activity involved in memory processes. I published several articles in peer-reviewed scientific journals, was awarded several major scholarships to support my research, and presented my work at international conferences. My specialties include data analysis, programming in MATLAB and R, scientific writing, op-ed writing, legal research and writing, event organization, collaborative work, public speaking. I'm also a visual artist, creating paintings to support social initiatives.

I am an experienced machine learning and text mining professional with 9 years of post-PhD experience in multiple domains, including online media and advertising, oil and gas, manufacturing, IT systems, healthcare and messaging.  I have acted as trusted machine learning advisor for start ups in the area of healthcare, smart messaging, autonomous IT systems, HR and retail. I worked as an assistant professor at prestigious Indian Institute of Technology (IIT) Madras in Computer Science and Engineering department.  I taught several Computer Science courses including popular course on Machine Learning, Computational Biology and Mathematical Foundations of Computer Science.  I advised 10+ graduate students in my academic tenure.  The complete list of my publications along with citations can be found on Google Scholar.With the mix of academic and industry experience, I specialize in formulating and addressing data driven problems with machine learning and related technologies. I was one of the nine recipients of Innovative Young Biotechnologist award from Department of Biotechnology  of Govt. of India in 2009.

summary:
My PhD research involves development of fast and memory efficient machine learning algorithms for sophisticated analysis of large-scale databases. The techniques I utilise include variational Bayesian approximations, Monte chain Monte Carlo methods, semi-parametric penalization, graphical models and scalable/real time prediction. The proposed algorithms are available in R and Fortran, and have been applied in a wide variety of medical and social science studies, which typically have data with complex grouped structure and nonlinear outcome-predictor relationships.I am highly experienced in programming in statistical software including R, SAS, Stata, Stan and (beginner: Python and MySQL). I have experience in writing peer-reviewed scientific papers and government reports, as well as presenting to both technical and lay audiences. I am always curious, eager to learn and have an entrepreneurial personality. I enjoy working with people from different analytical backgrounds and in a challenging and dynamic environment.

summary:
In my current position at Google, I work at the intersection of statistical modeling and large-scale engineering. In my previous role as Lead Data Scientist at Activision Blizzard, I worked on the development and implementation of machine learning algorithms for improving the user experience in games and using data to improve monetization.I've earned my PhD in machine learning and computational biology, during which I had the chance to work with excellent scientists at the Machine Learning in Biology group at Max Planck (Tuebingen, Germany), the Machine Learning Group at the Technical University of Berlin and finally in a ML/Comp-Bio group at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer center in NYC. After graduating, I spent one year at Microsoft Research as a post-doctoral researcher, where I worked on Machine Learning methods for statistical genetics. During these past years I've become what I would consider to be a data scientist - solving problems ranging from development of large-scale machine learning algorithms, handling complex data sets, visualization and performing large scale computation in a cluster environment (I'm the author of pythongrid, which is a small tool to compute on a sun grid engine). Going beyond method development, I'm passionate about software engineering, in particular in python and C++, and find it rewarding to engineer a working software solution, translating theory into practice.

headline: Software Engineer at Google
jobs: {'title': 'Software Engineer', 'company': 'Google', 'date_range': 'Sep 2016 – Present', 'location': 'Mountain View, CA', 'description': None}; {'title': 'Data Scientist', 'company': 'Urban Engines', 'date_range': 'Feb 2013 – Sep 2016', 'location': 'Los Altos, CA', 'description': "I'm working on commuter transit data in terms of behaviour reconstruction and prediction through statistical models and system control with incentive programs. My PhD research was concerned with user models for users in networks with path choice -- both in telecommunications and in transit. At Urban Engines, I am focusing on transit applications. More specifically, I see this area as an example of a multipath network of users trying to greedily maximise commuting experience while sharing common resources -- an applied, dynamic resource allocation problem. The challenging part of this project is that you can only predict the state of the network if your model of user behaviour reflects the way commuters behave in real life. Another major part of my work is the question how to visualise transit data of millions of commuters in an interactive way that is pleasing to the eye, highlights the problems, and allows informed decision making. Here are some questions that I find exciting to think about:-- What is the right way to offer incentives to shift users out of peak time traffic? What is a good mathematical model that reflects commuter behaviour in an incentive program? -- How do commuters behave inside a public transport system and what does their behaviour imply for the system? This is an example of a system that consists of many actors whose behaviour has to be accurately modeled in order to understand the whole system response.  -- How far can we push inferences about the state of the entire system if we have an advanced commuter model?"}; {'title': 'Internship', 'company': 'Nokia', 'date_range': 'Jul 2010 – Dec 2010', 'location': 'Espoo, Finland', 'description': 'At Nokia, I worked with Lars Eggert and Niko Kiukkonen on energy efficient loadbalancing for mobile devices with multiple data interfaces, such as Wifi and 3G/4G/LTE. I was interested in applying the load balancing capabilities of Multipath TCP (MPTCP) and deriving an energy efficient load balancer as a Markov decision problem that takes user behaviour into account. The main ideas are: -- Switching interfaces is costly: Whenever you switch data interfaces, you incur costs for scanning Wifi access points or going to higher energy states for mobile data connections. -- Not switching interfaces can be costly:Whenever data is sent on 3G, the interface goes into a higher energy state and potentially wastes energy when not sending anything after the initial burst. On the other hand, short bursts can be handled with low timeouts and low energy overhead on Wifi.-- Under constant load, some interfaces consume less powers than others:This is not surprising. But how do you make sure that if the user is going to download a large file, you are on the right interface?In general, I came up with a Markov decision problem that described user and interface behaviour. That produced a small state -> action rule table which can be embedded into each phone and updated depending on the usage profile of each user. We had a productive time together, wrote a paper, and handed in a patent:Saving Mobile Device Energy with Multipath TCP, Christopher Pluntke, Lars Eggert, and Niko Kiukkonen, MobiArch 2011Method for Multipath Scheduling Based on a Lookup Table, Christopher Pluntke, NikoKiukkonen, Lars Eggert, patent application, publication date 24/10/2013'}; {'title': 'Internship', 'company': 'Alcatel-Lucent', 'date_range': 'Aug 2009 – Dec 2009', 'location': 'Holmdel, New Jersey', 'description': 'Internship at Bell Labs. Research on Valiant Load Balancing (VLB) in optical backbone networks. VLB tries to break up traffic skews by introducing a randomised step into routing -- similar to randomised quick sort -- that produces a uniform traffic matrix which can be routed with easier means than taking all possible traffic skews into account.'}
summary:
I find the overlap of mathematical modelling of large system and interacting users in the real world fascinating and this is reflected in most work I do. While my PhD research focused on the modelling part (multipath TCP, data centers, and user models of incentive programs), my current assignment as data scientist at Urban Engines is a combination of large scale data analysis (prototyping cool ideas up to production coding), user modelling (incentive projects, for example Travel Smart Rewards, Singapore, www.travelsmartrewards.sg) and interactive visualisation of large scale transport data.

summary:
I am an experienced, technical executive that took the science-route-to-business. Currently, I have the pleasure of leading a team creating cloud-based services and applications for an influential industry.Specialties:Technical management, leadership, and strategy; cloud-based application engineering; devops; machine learning; product management.Technologies:Google Cloud Platform (GCP): Google Container Engine (GKE), Google Compute Engine (GCE), Cloud Pub/Sub, Google Cloud Storage (GCS), Google AppEngine (GAE), TensorFlow, Cloud SQL, Google Cloud Functions (GCF), Google Container Registry (GCR), Datastore, Cloud Dataflow, etc.DevOps: Docker, Kubernetes, CI/CD, CircleCILanguages: Python, JavaScript, C, C++, BASHMy Story:I started at the bottom writing application code mainly in C++, Java, and PHP. To deepen my skills and apply technology to an interesting problem, I pursued my PhD in theoretical biophysics (statistical thermodynamics). Toward the end of my PhD I became enamored by the power of machine learning and statistical decision-making. This lead me to pursue a postdoc in machine learning. jobs: {'title': 'Data Scientist', 'company': 'Google', 'date_range': 'Oct 2016 – Present', 'location': 'Mountain View', 'description': None}; {'title': 'Graduate Student', 'company': 'University of Minnesota', 'date_range': 'Aug 2012 – Aug 2016', 'location': 'Greater Minneapolis-St. Paul Area', 'description': 'My research is to introduce a new framework to model decision making under ambiguity that serves as a bridge between distributionally robust optimization and stochastic programming. We consider problems where uncertain variables follow distributions that are also unknown. The method attempts to balance the goals of providing a solution that is robust to this distributional ambiguity and effectively leveraging historical data. As in classic distributionally robust optimization, we hedge against distributional ambiguity by optimizing over a worse case distribution that satisfies some constraints. However, instead of using estimates for the moments, we partition the region and estimate conditional moments from historical data in order to derive constraints. Thus we restrict the class of distributions and therefore reduce conservativeness while retaining the advantage over a stochastic program of allowing for distributional ambiguity. As we increase the number of regions in the partition, we include more specific problem data but also have greater estimation errors. We derive a general formulation and demonstrate the computational tractability of the univariate case. In the multivariate case, we explore polygonal and combinations of ellipsoids and differences of ellipsoids partitions. We explore and derive formulations for two major applications: the newsvendor problem and facility location. We perform numerical experiments to evaluate the practical usefulness of conditional moments as compared to full moments and a stochastic approach.'}; {'title': 'Data Science Intern', 'company': 'Allstate', 'date_range': 'May 2015 – Aug 2015', 'location': 'Northbrook, IL', 'description': 'Informed decision making and strategy in agency analytics by using predictive modeling. summary:
I am an analytics-focused Data Scientist with special interests in predictive modeling and time series forecasting. My passion is data and understanding the patterns in seemingly-messy, unfiltered numbers. I work with R and SQL on a daily basis and have experience with a plethora of packages and tools. In my toolkit, I also use Python, SPSS, JMP, LaTex, and Excel. I hold a Masters in Statistics from Rice University in Houston, and Bachelors of Arts in Statistics and Psychology from Rice University, where I graduated in three years with cum laude honors.

headline: Sofware Engineer at Google Inc
jobs: {'title': 'Staff Engineer', 'company': 'Google Inc', 'date_range': 'Mar 2016 – Present', 'location': 'Mountain View', 'description': 'Currently, I am Staff Engineer at Google working on communications products.'}; {'title': 'Co-Founder and CTO', 'company': 'Bento Labs', 'date_range': 'May 2014 – Feb 2016', 'location': 'San Francisco Bay Area', 'description': "At Bento Labs we were building an AI aware distribution of Android. Our position was that while many aspects of the mobile OS were commoditized (touch, sensor, battery management etc) there was still significant room for innovation higher up the stack, especially in user attention management. While thephones in 2015 had 50x the CPU power, a lot more sensors, and an order of magnitude more bandwidth available to them than a decade before, there still were no good solutions for app discovery, data sharing between apps, or instant personalization on the phone. We believed that if we rethought the app model — what it means to be an app on the phone — and imbued the OS APIs with AI, we could solve some of these long-standing issues. Our first app was Scout Launcher (home-screen on Android) that figured out what information/services the user needed and when they needed it, and provided them right on the phone's home-screen. Our app was highly rated on the Play store (> 4.5 stars) and was used for > 30 mins everyday by its users.Our team had experience at companies like Google, Yahoo, RelateIQ, Coursera, VMware etc., and they were passionate about improving the phone experience for billions of people around the world."}; {'title': 'Advisor', 'company': 'A Big Data start-up', 'date_range': 'Sep 2013 – Aug 2015', 'location': None, 'description': '- helping them with their machine learning algorithms'}; {'title': 'Data Products Engineering', 'company': 'RelateIQ', 'date_range': 'Jan 2012 – Jan 2014', 'location': None, 'description': 'I was the 4th engineer at RelateIQ and I led the Data Products Engineering team; I built data products that mine and deliver relationship intelligence within the app. Some of the products I worked on are below.1) Automated suggestions to follow-up with contacts based on context of communication (including content of emails).  2) Contact management features such as contact-deduplication and extraction of contact information from email signatures.3) Algorithms to automatic construction of a sales process; such as automatically determining when to add a contact to a sales account. 4) Automatically determining the closest connection of the sales team to a sales lead.5) Machine learning models for parsing emails, extracting content from emails and webpages, and measuring strength of relationships.The techniques I used included various kinds of unsupervised analysis, natural language processing, some supervised learning, and lots and lots of hacks.'}; {'title': 'Senior Research Scientist', 'company': 'Yahoo!', 'date_range': 'Aug 2007 – May 2012', 'location': None, 'description': '- Measuring Impacts on User Engagement: I led this project in which we developed a system to measure the impact of user-experience changes on long-term engagement of users. Our emphasis was on deriving causal links relying mainly on pre-existing (observational) log-data; i.e. without having to run randomized experiments. The first study quantitatively characterized the impact of spam-exposure on long-term user-engagement.- Modeling Social Systems: I extensively researched social system dynamics: modeling the reasons why users link to each other, the propagation of trends, and the production of content on social systems.- Mining Hidden User Intent: I worked extensively on modeling the observed behavior of users to mine their hidden intents. This work resulted in systems to help determine the user intent in ambiguous web search queries (mining facets), in computational advertising systems (commercial intent in queries), and social systems (the reason behind linking).- Web Search Systems: I worked on many layers of the web-search technology stack: from devising low-level indexing and early-termination optimizations all the way up to improving the display of search results (summarizing tweets, shortening page-titles, generating quicklinks and query-suggestions, etc.)- Abuse Detection and Prevention: In this long-running project I developed systems for mail- spam detection, detection and prevention of phishing, design and stress-tests of CAPTCHAs, and data mining of logs to detect abusive behavior.'}
summary:
Currently, I am Staff Engineer at Google working on communications products. Before this I was Co-Founder and CTO of Bento Labs where we are working on building an AI enabled OS for Android devices. There I recruited a team of talented engineers from RelateIQ, Coursera, and VMware, and built and launched our first product, Scout Launcher, which was highly rated on the Android Play store (> 4.5 stars) and used for > 30 mins each day by its users. Previously, I was the 4th engineer at RelateIQ where I led the Data Products Engineering team that built data products that mine and deliver relationship intelligence within our app; for example, automated suggestions to follow-up with contacts. The techniques I used included various kinds of unsupervised analysis, natural language processing, some supervised learning, and lots and lots of hacks. Before RelateIQ, I was a Senior Research Scientist at Yahoo! Research. There the common theme in all my work was the analysis of “Big data” to improve systems like web search, computational advertising, behavioral targeting, online abuse prevention, and to mine insights to drive business decisions. My academic background broadly is Machine Learning, Data Mining, and Algorithms and I got my PhD at Univ of Texas - Austin. A partial list of my academic work can be found at http://www.ideal.ece.utexas.edu/~kunal/work.html

The diffusion model is a novel and theoretical sound way to estimate reaction times to two-choice decision processes. For example, consider working on a true/false portion of a test, where you to want to get the answers correct (why else would you be taking a test?) while you\'re put underneath a time constraint - i.e. you need to finish the test in time. Under these conditions, one could imagine that how much time you might take to reach a conclusion could be proportional to how difficult a question is. Thus we can view the accumulation of reasoning that you might take until you reach a decision to effect your reaction time to answering a question; And you could visualize the "path" of reasoning that you may have to be straight - i.e. the answer is obvious to you, or the "path" may be winding, which may be when the answer is not obvious. All of this intuition basically leads to the diffusion model, which is an analytic model that measures how your cognitive processes in decision making is related to your reaction time. In technical terms, the diffusion model is based off of Markov Chains (each iteration represents a decision making process), where the state is indexed by time, (this is essentially a stochastic process). The steady state for each chain is a decision (either correct or error). The diffusion model reflects both reaction time and accuracy, and therefore is very flexible plenty of data types. Some of my interest stems from this, and the fitting/estimation procedure for the diffusion model.'}; {'title': 'Supervisor', 'company': 'Krannert Center For the Performing Arts', 'date_range': 'Aug 2012 – May 2013', 'location': None, 'description': None}; {'title': 'Technical Specialist', 'company': 'Parkland College', 'date_range': 'May 2011 – Aug 2012', 'location': None, 'description': None}

summary:
Big data, small data, blue data, green data and everything in between ... data. I am a Statistician and Data Scientist with a passion for solving compelling problems using tools from the interface of Computer Science, Statistics, and Operations Research. I have worked in various industries, including insurance, agriculture, education, research, and consumer measurement. My workflow typically includes some form of the R and/or Python data science stack, with departures in C/C++, Java, Scala, and associated technologies. I also am a natural born teacher. I have taught both graduate school courses in statistics and corporate training seminars in Pythonic data science methods. One of my joys is witnessing the progression of learning in an individual, and these experiences have helped me learn significant lessons about communicating convoluted information cogently. I've been tremendously lucky to study at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign for both my B.S. in Statistics and my M.S. in Statistics. While there I worked as both a Undergraduate Research Assistant in the Adult Learning Lab and Graduate Teaching Assistant for the Lipka Lab.I am excited to be apart of the data science revolution. If you'd like to learn more about my interests, please visit my personal site at kylenpayne.github.ioPlease note: I am Kyle Nicholas Payne, not Kyle Dean Payne. This will be useful information if you end up googling me.

summary:
I am a data scientist at Google Medical Brain applying epidemiological, statistical, machine learning, and deep learning methods on large data sets. I specialized in modeling pediatric nervous system trajectories using linear mixed models while obtaining my master’s degree and antiretroviral therapy regimen modification among HIV patients failing primary therapy using targeted estimation in semi-parametric models for my doctorate. My professional research includes (i) survival analysis in both randomized controlled trials and observational studies, (ii) targeted and efficient estimation of causal effects in semi-parametric models, and (iii) loss-based machine learning ensemble prediction algorithms.I'm also a licensed Emergency Medical Technician. During my down time and in emergencies, I like volunteering my time and effort towards helping those in need.

summary:
Mario Callegaro is senior survey scientist at Google Cloud UX, London. He focuses on User Experience research involving surveys and consults on numerous projects in terms of survey design, questionnaire design, sampling, and reporting.Mario holds a M.S. and a Ph.D. in Survey Research and Methodology from the University of Nebraska, Lincoln. Prior to joining Google, Mario was working as survey research scientist for Gfk-Knowledge Networks. He is associate editor of Survey Research Methods and in the editorial board of the International Journal of Market Research.Current research areas: web survey design, smart-phone surveys, telephone / cell phone surveys, and questionnaire design in which he has published numerous papers, book chapters and conference presentations. Mario published an edited book (May 2014): Online Panel Research: A Data Quality Perspective (Wiley publisher) and his monograph titled: "Web Survey Methodology" is available from Sage as of June 2015

I collaborated with a talented team of machine learning and software development experts to conceptualize, prototype and deploy novel ML algorithms.'}; {'title': 'Graduate Student Researcher', 'company': 'University of California, Riverside', 'date_range': 'Sep 2009 – Jul 2016', 'location': 'University of California Riverside, Brookhaven National Lab', 'description': 'I earned my PhD in 2016, working with a research group studying spin physics at the University of California Riverside for Dr. Ken Barish in collaboration with the PHENIX experiment at Brookhaven National Lab. I was involved with experimental operations and analysis of data sets at many levels. I worked with petabyte scale data sets, engineered data pipelines, and carried out analyses in an international collaboration.I applied machine learning techniques in conjunction with custom designed hardware to categorize rare particle events, in order to separate these rare events from a high noise background. I collaborated with a global team of researchers to construct and troubleshoot resistive plate chambers, which were integrated into the PHENIX detector in 2012. I developed and maintained software responsible for the fast production of physics data from raw data using a condor cluster during the subsequent 2012 and 2013 physics data periods at PHENIX using the Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider. I identified and patched several software performance bottlenecks as part of this work. I also engineered the software systems responsible for monitoring the proton-spin polarization of our colliding beams - a task which was crucial to maintaining data usability and quality.My thesis research focused on understanding the Quantum Chromodynamic origin of the proton spin. I studied the fraction of total proton spin contributed by sea-quarks via colliding polarized protons at 510 GeV center of mass energy in the electroweak decay channel. I studied the W boson decay produced in these collisions, to gain direct access to the helicity distribution sea-quarks, which in turn, provided a window into anti-quark contribution to proton spin.I facilitated the extraction of this result from the 2013 data set, partaking in all phases of the analysis, including hardware testing and implementation, online data production management, and offline data analysis and quality assurance testing.'}; {'title': 'Data Science Fellow', 'company': 'Insight Data Science', 'date_range': 'Jan 2016 – Apr 2016', 'location': None, 'description': 'I built the web application, www.aletrailbeers.com, which guided users to new beers and breweries using machine learning to classify and represent the flavors in beer graphically. The app produced a map to local California beers, to obtain beer matched to user preferences. The back end of the application utilized machine learning applied to natural language to score to a corpus of over 10,000 California microbrews characterizing the beer as "hoppy" or "malty". This was accomplished using a Naive Bayes Classification system, and web-scraping from the website \'beeradvocate.com\', as well as word-frequency analysis, and the python "NLTK" library. Data ingested included numerically scored reviews, style-labels, and brewery contact information. Beers were located geographically using the Yelp API.The front end of the website used a customized twitter bootstrap template, Flask, a PostgreSQL database, as well as the Google Maps API, to pinpoint various beers to user-selected regions. Additionally, I engineered a lightweight, word-stemming search engine to filter recommendations generated after users selected a graphical description of beer-flavors based on flavor classification and review word frequency.I was able to create this product from start to finish, rapidly learning most of the relevant techniques along the way in only four weeks.'}; {'title': 'Graduate Teaching Assistant', 'company': 'University of California, Riverside', 'date_range': 'Sep 2009 – Sep 2015', 'location': 'Riverside, CA', 'description': 'I taught undergraduate physics lab sections as well as undergraduate discussion sections for introductory physics courses including: "How Things Work - A non mathematical Introduction to Modern Physics", "Nuclear Physics", "Classical Electromagnetism", "Classical Mechanics" and "Thermodynamics". I was honored to receive two teaching awards for this work, being singled out from a pool of the top 1% of teaching assistants at UC Riverside.'}; {'title': 'Undergraduate Researcher', 'company': 'Western Washington University', 'date_range': 'Mar 2008 – Jun 2009', 'location': 'Western Washington University', 'description': "I worked with Dr. Takele Seda at Western Washington University to carry out research supported by the Advanced Materials Science and Engineering Center (AMSEC) and the Nasa Space Grant Fellowship aimed to study the super-paramagnetic phase and magnetic properties of nanoscale magnetite. The research's aim was to develop a novel liquid phase colloidal synthesis of mangetite nanoparticles and investigate methods of doping the magnetite, as well as characterizing the the particle's properties using Mossbauer Spectroscopy and X-Ray diffraction. The research had various applications in targeted medication delivery.Skills developed as part of this research include: X-Ray diffraction crystallography, Mossbauer Spectroscopy, basic micro-emulsion temperature-controlled chemical synthesis methods, basic chemistry, laboratory management, freeze drying chemical-precipitate extraction methods, centrifuge chemical-precipitate extraction methods, chemical safety management, and liquid phase colloidal synthesis methods."}; {'title': 'Undergraduate Teaching Assistant', 'company': 'Western Washington University', 'date_range': 'Sep 2007 – Jun 2009', 'location': None, 'description': 'I was an undergraduate teaching assistant teaching and running labs for undergraduate physics classes. I have over seven years of research experience, focusing primarily on using genomic and statistical analyses to help solve biomedical problems such as cancer and malaria.These experiences helped me realize that my passion involves more than exploring just the theoretical implications of big data -- I want to transform that data into trends, models, and conclusions that can make a practical impact on people and organizations.  Now that I've finished my program at Yale, I am looking to work with a team of smart, energetic people who are just as excited about using the power of informatics for good as I am.I love working on big problems -- I would love to hear about yours!

I have been a machine learning engineer and researcher for 18 years, in addition to spending time in game development roles. The vast majority of my experience has been at the senior engineer level and above.Put simply, I build large-scale systems in production settings.My primary machine learning focus is on text and natural language processing, although I have built systems in several other domains - information retrieval, workflow optimization, active learning, predictive modeling. My research, done over the last several years under a grant from the National Science Foundation, has largely involved object representation and recognition, mainly in the text and image processing realm. As a game developer one of my main tasks was the optimization of a highly complex and scalable in-house engine which has, to date, powered a series of more than a dozen games.As a programmer, I have a passion for optimization - pipeline, project, compiler, and software.  I work most often in C++, Python, and C#, but have built products using most languages at one point or another.I spent 2014-2015 competing extensively on Kaggle.com (a popular international platform for predictive modelling competitions), and still compete occasionally. At end of this process, the stabilized biomass presents high levels of nutrients, which can be used both as biofertilizers in agriculture and for the biodegradation of contaminants in the soil through improvement of microbiota. Thus, this study aimed to evaluate biogas production by industrial wastes and to use the biofertilizer for the bioremediation of soils previously contaminated with gasoline. Anaerobic incubation reduced total and volatile solids, as well as biochemical oxygen demand, chemical oxygen demand, and carbon and nitrogen contents of the biomass. The bioremediation experiment showed that 30 days after contamination of the soil, both contaminated soil (SC) and the contaminated soil with added biofertilizer (SBC) presented an equal reduction in theamount of aromatic hydrocarbons. Fifteen days after contamination, the addition of the biofertilizer improved the degradation efficiency of mono-aromatic hydrocarbons; however, the degradation of poly-aromatic hydrocarbons was less efficient. school: University of Pennsylvania - The Wharton School
summary:
I’m a data guy. Since my school days, I have been passionate about helping businesses gain a competitive edge in the marketplace and increase profits through Big Data. Throughout my career, I have had the opportunity to apply my technical know-how while working with industry leaders in technology, management, and finance. Though I have held leadership roles for years, I decided to enhance my business acumen further by pursuing my M.B.A. With a concentration in Marketing and Strategic Management, I earned my degree from Wharton School of Business. While I could write (another!) book on ways to use Big Data to spur bottom-line revenue, here are some of my favorites:COMPETITIVE DIFFERENTIATIONMany companies possess vast amounts of data on businesses and customers. By tapping into these insights and leveraging them strategically, I identify ways to differentiate services/products from competitors. PRODUCT DEVELOPMENTMuch of my career has involved conceptualizing ways data-related products can be monetized and guiding teams to build these products and services.TARGET MARKETINGBy using quantitative and qualitative market research to more narrowly target audiences, I work closely with marketing leaders to increase the ROI of sales and advertising campaigns. In addition, I collaborate with engineers to target customers with new products.Even though I am now a true business professional, I do have a background in academia. While working toward my Ph.D. and my Post-Doctoral Fellowship in Artificial Intelligence, I published academic papers, presented at international conferences, and taught programming and computing classes to undergraduate students. In fact, I earned a Wharton MBA Grant and Sainsbury Management Fellowship from the Royal Academy of Engineering due to my leadership background and stellar academic record.More than anything, I enjoy guiding organizations in optimizing ALL of their data. I truly find building new data-focused businesses fun!
